Date: Mon, 14 Mar 2005 20:43:51 +0200
From: J. Wicht <jwicht@kingsley.co.za>

[Re: Nick Honhold's comments in ProMED post 20050313.0738 of 3 Mar 2005,
Salmonellosis, kebab shop - UK (London)(02)]
The origin of the word avoirdupois apart, I think of these measures as
grains, drams, ounces, pounds etc. Cloves and tods were units used in
weighing wool -- thus a clove equals 7 pounds, a stone equals 14 pounds, a
tod equals 2 stone, a wey equals 6 and a half tod, a pack equals 240 pounds,
a sack equals 2 weys, and a last equals 12 sacks. How interesting life was
in pre-decimal days!
--
Jan Wicht
<jwicht@kingsley.co.za>
[This is fascinating. So I weigh a bit more than a wey, a stone and a
clove -- or just over a half sack, which doesn't sound quite so heavy! (I am
2 and 1/9 yards tall, however, so my body mass index is OK. - Mod.JW]
