[2]
Date: Mon, 14 Mar 2005 14:32:12 EST
From: Richard Brown MRCVS<rexrocco@aol.com>

We had a long discussion in our practice re units now in use in the UK. One
of our colleagues (Belgian) is very pro-metric, while older folk such as
myself enjoy the intellectual exercise of working 2 systems.
One bizarre conclusion we came to is that many of the non-metric measures
will stay either because they are related to biological measures (inch and
foot), or convenience (pint), or for ladiesï¿½ diplomacy (stones and pounds
are weights that allow for latitude in interpretation), or simple
practicality: a crate of wine bottles has to have 12 to be properly packed.
The latter hints at the mathematical power of a system which includes the
number 12.
In conclusion, this side of the pond, non-metric units (I dare not say
imperial!) will continue to pop up.
--
Richard Brown MRCVS
Strathbogie Vet Centre
Huntly, Aberdeenshire., UK
<rexrocco@aol.com>
[In the pre-decimal days we were weighed in stones. I always wondered why
such a clumsy method was used when livestock were weighed in pounds, and
grain in hundredweights. I suppose we were regarded as woolly-headed. -
Mod.MHJ]
[Men lie about their weight too. - Copyeditor PG]
